<H3> <TI>   Djukanovic on `Unrealistic' Hopes on Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Djukanovic on `Unrealistic' Hopes on Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305151394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1125 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1305151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION>, 13 May (TANJUG) -- Montenegrin Prime 
Minister <PERSON>Milo Djukanovic</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE> that the hopes that 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, as part of the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION>, will 
be given somewhat different treatment as regards sanctions are 
unrealistic. The international community is not even 
considering a partial relaxation of sanctions against <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> 
alone, and such a solution "would not be good for either 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION>," he said. 
  Speaking about a possible lifting of the sanctions against 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, which has been talked about increasingly often among 
the public, <PERSON>Djukanovic</PERSON> said at a news conference that the only 
relaxation that <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> could expect is the reestablishing of 
traffic links with <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> and somewhat more generous humanitarian 
aid, due to the large numbers of refugees. 
  The Montenegrin prime minister stressed that the awareness 
of 
how senseless the sanctions are is gaining strength in the 
international community, for it is being realized that they have 
not achieved their objective. Asked how much the sanctions have 
cost <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Djukanovic</PERSON> said that the "amount of the losses" 
cannot be precisely quantified. However, he added, the lost 
exports and revenue from tourism, the non-functioning of the 
merchant fleet, and the inability to meet contractual 
obligations to foreign partners have so far cost <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> some 
<MONEY>$3.34 billion</MONEY>. 
  Speaking about new economic measures, <PERSON>Djukanovic</PERSON> mentioned a 
possible increase in salaries in the republic, but warned they 
have to be kept in line with other parameters, particularly with 
production. 

</TEXT>

