<H3> <TI>   Djukanovic Assesses Sanctions After UK Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Djukanovic Assesses Sanctions After UK Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806114694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1042 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1806114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION>, 18 Jun (TANJUG) -- Significant headway 
has been achieved in the talks conducted by the Montenegrin 
delegation in <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION>, because there is a growing 
awareness that the policy of sanctions against the <ORGANIZATION>Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> is pointless, Montenegrin 
Prime Minister <PERSON>Milo Djukanovic</PERSON> said in his assessment of the 
Montenegrin delegation's visit to <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION>. The delegation 
returned to <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION> <DATE>yesterday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>. 
  The stands of the international community -- primarily the 
<LOCATION>European Union</LOCATION> -- on the futility of the policy of sanctions, 
which have, in a way, been conveyed to the Montenegrin 
delegation will, according to <PERSON>Djukanovic</PERSON>, encourage a flurry of 
activity leading to the establishment of peace in 
<LOCATION>Bosnia-Herzegovina</LOCATION>, after which the sanctions against the 
<ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION> will be alleviated. 
  Assessing the talks in <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION> as extremely useful and 
interesting, the Montenegrin prime minister stressed that it had 
been mutually noted that peace in <LOCATION>Bosnia-Herzegovina</LOCATION> is of 
paramount importance, and that this will be followed by all 
other moves on the part of the international community. 
  Respect was also voiced toward the principled policies 
pursued by <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, both in the sense of searching for a 
solution in the region of former <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION> and of normalizing 
the situation in the entire area, <PERSON>Djukanovic</PERSON> said. He attaches 
great importance to the fact that, by making this visit, 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>'s foreign policy, which does carry a certain amount 
of weight in the eyes of the international community, has 
announced the beginning of a new diplomatic offensive. 

</TEXT>

