<H3> <TI>   FRY To Join Telecommunication Network </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FRY To Join Telecommunication Network </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005210794 Podgorica POBJEDA in Serbo-Croatian 17 May 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> AU3005210794 </F>
<F P=104>  Podgorica POBJEDA </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Article by <PERSON>N. Perkovic</PERSON>: "Under the Sea Into the World"] </F>
  [Text] <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION>, 16 <DATE>May 1994</DATE> -- Owing to a project made 
possible by the <ORGANIZATION>OTE</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Greek Telecommunications Organization</ORGANIZATION>, 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION> will not remain a desert island in the 
"sea" of international telecommunications. A part of the <MONEY>$3.5 
million</MONEY> equipment for digital radio-relay connections, which had 
been bought by <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> from the Italian company 
"Alcatel-Teletra" before the sanctions were introduced, will be 
delivered to <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> via <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>. Beginning from <DATE>September 
1996</DATE>, <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> should have an underwater connection from Bar, 
through <LOCATION>Durres</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Corfu</LOCATION>, to the whole world. 
  This is the result of the agreement achieved in <LOCATION>Salonika</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION> between the Yugoslav and Montenegrin <ORGANIZATION>PTT</ORGANIZATION> and the 
representatives of the Greek telecommunication service. In 
<LOCATION>Salonika</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Vucic Cagorovic</PERSON>, the Yugoslav <ORGANIZATION>PTT</ORGANIZATION> general manager, 
<PERSON>Milorad Jaksic</PERSON>, the Serbian <ORGANIZATION>PTT</ORGANIZATION> general manager, and <PERSON>Jusuf 
Fetahovic</PERSON>, the Montenegrin <ORGANIZATION>PTT</ORGANIZATION> general manager, concluded the 
work of expert groups from both countries. 
  There followed a meeting of expert groups in <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION>, led by 
<PERSON>Jusuf Fetahovic</PERSON> and <PERSON>Petros Labron</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>OTE</ORGANIZATION> general manager, in 
which the agreement was reached that <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> should be 
included in every project for optic cables planned for the 
<LOCATION>Adriatic</LOCATION>. 
  Experts consider that the <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY> investment in the 
radio-relay and optic cables project will be the most profitable 
investment in <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>. Therefore it is considered that this 
historic endeavor will be fervently supported by the <ORGANIZATION>Montenegrin 
Government</ORGANIZATION>, especially if we know that both <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> and the 
<ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION> would profit from it because this 
would enable them to become linked to the international 
communication network. Otherwise they would not only be cut off 
from the world and deprived of the possibility of following 
scientific achievements in this field, but they would also lose 
an important income in hard currency. 
  Taking into consideration all parameters, this will be the 
most profitable ecological and tourist undertaking in the 
ecological state of <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> [as published]. 

</TEXT>

