<H3> <TI>   Gasoline Smuggled From Albania to Montenegro </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20355A Ljubljana DELO in Slovene 29 Jan 94 p 20 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20355A </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana DELO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Branko Jokic</PERSON>: "Business Is Business"] </F>
  [Text] (From our correspondent) <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION>, 28 <DATE>January</DATE> -- 
According to an article published in the Novi Pazar magazine 
<LOCATION>SANDZAK</LOCATION>, Montenegrin and Albanian authorities concluded a secret 
agreement on the export of gasoline from <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, 
from where it is delivered to Pale [capital of the <LOCATION>Srpska</LOCATION> 
republic] to be used by the Bosnian Serb military. 
  According to the article, Montenegrin Albanians living along 
the Montenegrin-Albanian border are involved in the deals. Some 
of them have been licensed by the <ORGANIZATION>Montenegrin Government</ORGANIZATION> to 
"import" gasoline. Gasoline, which costs one German mark per 
liter in the Albanian town of <LOCATION>Scutari</LOCATION>, is transported in large 
quantities across <LOCATION>Lake Skutari</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Yugoslav Army</ORGANIZATION> 
provides specially equipped boats. 
  The citizens of <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> involved in this business earn 
one-half mark per liter. Almost all local residents participate 
in this trade (actually it is a state-sanctioned smuggling 
operation) because of the high earnings. <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> and the 
<LOCATION>Srpska</LOCATION> republic are well supplied with gasoline. The <ORGANIZATION>Pizon 
Petrol Enterprise</ORGANIZATION>, owned by the former <ORGANIZATION>Crvena Zvezda</ORGANIZATION> soccer 
player <PERSON>Vladimir Petrovic Pizon</PERSON>, transports gasoline from <LOCATION>Lake 
Scutari</LOCATION> to Pale. 
  As reported, the Albanian authorities have recently 
tightened 
control over gasoline sales in <LOCATION>Scutari</LOCATION>, but it is a well-known 
secret that gasoline stations in <ORGANIZATION>Scutari</ORGANIZATION> work at full speed and 
sell almost half of all the gasoline sold in <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION>. We are 
talking about very large quantities, knowing that last year 
Albanians registered several thousand vehicles that they had 
purchased at European junkyards. According to the article, Pale 
receives five to seven tanker-truck loads of Albanian gasoline 
each day. 
  In addition to <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Macedonia</LOCATION> is also accused of 
sanctions violations. At the border crossings near <LOCATION>Ohrid</LOCATION> and 
<PERSON>Rozaj</PERSON> (on the Macedonian-Albanian and Montenegrin-Albanian 
borders), aluminum is exported from <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> and raw materials 
are imported for <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION> without hindrance. Heavy 
trucks and trailers wait for hours on both sides of the border 
crossings, which in the past were almost without traffic. 
  If all this is true, we could conclude that this type of 
border trade, uncontrolled by representatives of the 
international community, was agreed to by <PERSON>Momir Bulatovic</PERSON> and 
<PERSON>Sali Berisha</PERSON> when the Montenegrin president visited <LOCATION>Tirana</LOCATION>. At 
the same time, Montenegrin Prime Minister <PERSON>Milo Djukanovic</PERSON> paid a 
visit to <LOCATION>Skopje</LOCATION>. It is a fact that we can only guess now how 
<LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> benefits. Maybe it is alleviation of discontent in the 
western part of the country, where at least some hundred local 
residents are earning good incomes trafficking in gasoline. 

</TEXT>

