<H3> <TI>   Discusses Peace Issues With Hurd </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Peace Issues With Hurd </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406214494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1914 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, 14 Jun (TANJUG) -- British Foreign Secretary 
<PERSON>Douglas Hurd</PERSON> today received a Montenegrin delegation headed by 
Prime Minister <PERSON>Milo Djukanovic</PERSON>. 
  The Montenegrin delegation was received this afternoon by 
<PERSON>Douglas Hogg</PERSON>, state minister at the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION>, and visited 
the <ORGANIZATION>British Council</ORGANIZATION>. 
  The Montenegrin delegation also includes Deputy Prime 
Minister <PERSON>Kruno Vukcevic</PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON>Miodrag Lekic</PERSON>. 
  It has been learned from the delegation that the talks 
centred on the crisis in former <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, especially the 
search for a peaceful solution in Bosnia-Hezcegovina. The hosts 
asked the Montenegrin delegation to convey their appeal to the 
Yugoslav side to help in the establishment of peace in <LOCATION>Bosnia</LOCATION> by 
influencing the Bosnian Serbs to accept the proposed 51:49 
territorial ratio. 
  According to <PERSON>Milo Djukanovic</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> will do all it can 
to find a peaceful solution as soon as possible. 
  The hosts were also informed about the consequences of the 
international sanctions on the Montenegrin economy, and the 
government delegation requested <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s aid in opening a ferry 
line to <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> for humanitarian reasons, and to enable the 
blocked Montenegrin ships to return to their home ports. 
  The Montenegrin delegation will be meeting members of the 
British-Yugoslav group in the <LOCATION>British Parliament</LOCATION> tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

