<TEXT>
CSO 

    [Editorial Report] South Slav media have been carrying 
reports that the Yugoslav military leadership has become 
increasingly worried about troop morale. Fewer and fewer 
soldiers are going to war voluntarily, and the authorities in 
<LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> have had to resort to forceful 
mobilization of Serb refugees. Commenting on this issue in a 3 
<DATE>February</DATE> interview on <LOCATION>Sarajevo</LOCATION> radio, Bosnian President <PERSON>Alija 
Izetbegovic</PERSON> said that the Yugoslav military may be suffering a 
"shortage of manpower" and having problems with "the morale of 
that manpower." 
  In the 17 <DATE>March</DATE> issue of the <LOCATION>Ljubljana</LOCATION> daily DNEVNIK, the 
<ORGANIZATION>Slovene Press Agency</ORGANIZATION> [STA] reports that few conscripts are 
responding to call-ups in <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>. Many of them obtain 
medical certificates attesting that they are physically 
incapable of serving in the armed forces. Quoting the <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION> 
weekly LIBERAL, STA states that such false medical certificates 
are sold by draft officers at a high price, adding that many 
reservists prefer going to jail to enlisting for the "defense of 
the fatherland." According to the report, the military police 
are quite active, picking up draftees on the streets and 
delivering them to military barracks. 
  STA reports that the "action" is supposedly coordinated by 
Major <PERSON>Veselin Sljivancanin</PERSON>, a "man on the wanted list" and the 
"hero of <LOCATION>Vukovar</LOCATION>." As commander of the 5th Motorized Brigade of 
the <LOCATION>Podgorica Corps</LOCATION>, he is also in charge of all Montenegrin 
draft boards. According to "well-informed sources," he was sent 
from <LOCATION>Belgrade</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> to "put military affairs in order 
and raise the morale of the military." "Other sources" claim 
that his assignment is to prevent the possible secession of 
<LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> from the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, if necessary 
by utilizing the "methods he employed in <LOCATION>Vukovar</LOCATION>." Examining his 
role in <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION>, the 5 <DATE>November</DATE> issue of the <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION> 
opposition weekly MONITOR concludes that <PERSON>Sljivancanin</PERSON>, "a lover 
of the Socialist Party of <LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION>" and a proven fighter for the 
"Serbian cause," had been sent to exert "federal" pressure on 
the <ORGANIZATION>Montenegrin Government</ORGANIZATION>. Although he was allegedly received 
"cooly" by his immediate superior, General <PERSON>Milorad Obradovic</PERSON>, 
MONITOR reports, many people feel that <PERSON>Sljivancanin</PERSON> might remain 
in <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION> permanently, while others believe that his 
assignment must be viewed as a "temporary solution" within the 
context of personnel changes in the <ORGANIZATION>Yugoslav Army</ORGANIZATION>. 

</TEXT>

