<H3> <TI>   Authorities Close Road Link With Montenegro </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities Close Road Link With Montenegro </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0706132894 Paris AFP in English 1300 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0706132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Podgorica</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, <DATE>June 7</DATE> (AFP) -- The only 
road link between <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> has been closed to 
traffic for five days, a local daily reported <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. The 
Albanian authorities have forbidden any vehicles from crossing 
into or out of <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> -- which together with <LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION> forms 
rump-Yugoslavia -- at <LOCATION>Bozaj</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Lazar Jankovic</PERSON>, spokesman for 
the <ORGANIZATION>Yugoslav Commission for Border Incidents</ORGANIZATION>, quoted <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> by 
the local daily POBJEDA. The road is open to pedestrians. 
  The Albanian authorties apparently took the action after 
Albanian truck drivers had blocked the border because, <PERSON>Jankovic</PERSON> 
said, they were "unhappy at the changing criteria imposed by 
Yugoslav customs officials." Since a total embargo was imposed 
on <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION> two years ago, the Bozaj border-control post has 
become the focus of traffic in oil and other supplies for the 
Yugoslav market. Several Montenegrins were arrested recently by 
Albanians for trafficking oil, according to rumours which 
Montengrin authorities refuse to confirm. 
  PJOBEDA said it had learnt from unoffical sources that six 
policemen and a Montenegrin customs officer were being 
questioned for their role in the trafficking. 

</TEXT>

