<H3> <TI>   Djukanovic Comments on Relations With Albania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Djukanovic Comments on Relations With Albania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506173194 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1530 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1506173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Montenegrin Prime Minister <PERSON>Milo 
Djukanovic</PERSON> is paying an official visit to <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION>. We 
have established a direct link with <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> where Mr. Prime 
Minister [<ORGANIZATION>Djukanovic</ORGANIZATION>] is. Good day! 
  [<ORGANIZATION>Djukanovic</ORGANIZATION>] Good day! 
  [Announcer] To get right to the point for the listeners of 
Argument Vise [An Argument More] program -- what is the 
objective of your visit to <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION>, have you had any 
concrete meetings and talks? 
  [<ORGANIZATION>Djukanovic</ORGANIZATION>] Together with the deputy prime minister and 
Montenegrin foreign minister I am visiting <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> at the 
invitation of one of the members of the foreign affairs' 
committee of the lower chamber of the <ORGANIZATION>British Parliament</ORGANIZATION>. This 
afternoon I am supposed to present my vision of the current 
situation in <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION> in this lower chamber committee. 
  [Announcer] I presume that we will obtain some concrete 
information about your talks there later in the day. 
  [<ORGANIZATION>Djukanovic</ORGANIZATION>] Hello? 
  [Announcer] Yes, we can hear you. Rather optimistic 
assessments have been coming from <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION>, to which you paid an 
official visit beforehand -- that is, mutual satisfaction with 
this visit. Could you say anything more about it for our 
listeners? 
  [<ORGANIZATION>Djukanovic</ORGANIZATION>] I took the opportunity of the fact that I was 
travelling to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> via <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> to hold talks with the <ORGANIZATION>Albanian 
Government</ORGANIZATION>. We held talks with Prime Minister <PERSON>Meksi</PERSON>, naturally, 
in the presence of the foreign minister and other government 
officials. We discussed the need to intensify mutual relations. 
We took the opportunity to tell <PERSON>Mr. Meksi</PERSON> that the overall 
foreign affairs' goal of the FRY [Federal Republic of 
<LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>] is to establish good relations with its neighbors 
and that, within this context, <LOCATION>Montenegro</LOCATION> has an explicit need 
to establish good, that is to say, better relations with 
<LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION>, with whom it borders directly, than we have had in the 
past. On that occasion, we discussed some essential issues that 
represent the most important segments of the improvement of 
mutual relations -- the rights of minorities in both countries 
and some vital issues that we perceive as a possibility to 
promote economic and other cooperation. 
  I received assurances that, in accordance with the 
democratic 
changes that are underway in that country, the rights of the 
Serbs and the Montenegrins who live in <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> will receive 
appropriate treatment parallel to a demand that such a policy be 
pursued for the Albanians in the <ORGANIZATION>FRY</ORGANIZATION>. 
  Naturally, as always, special interest was shown in the 
problem of <LOCATION>Kosovo</LOCATION>. It seems that there have been some ambiguous 
statements by some diplomatic representatives of some 
superpowers -- I am primarily referring to the statements that 
have been coming from <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> recently -- which have contributed 
a lot that <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION> abandoned the aggressive attitude toward the 
<ORGANIZATION>FRY</ORGANIZATION> regarding <LOCATION>Kosovo</LOCATION>, acknowledged that <LOCATION>Kosovo</LOCATION> is an integral 
part of <LOCATION>Serbia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, and that this issue can only be 
discussed at the level of rights that must be guaranteed to the 
citizens of Albanian ethnicity in <LOCATION>Kosovo</LOCATION>. 
  I would say that for me all together this was a sign that a 
new leaf has been turned in the attitudes toward this issue and 
in the general FRY-Albanian relations. 
  [Announcer] Thank you very much. We wish you all success in 
you visit and activities in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>

